One problem you didn't touch with "faster rates of global warming" is that ground based temperature data is where the majority of the warming is being observed. The problem with this, is that the majority of the long term stations are situated in areas that WERE in undeveloped locations, but are NOW surrounded by development. The "Urban Heat Island Effect" is biasing the temperature data up, in proportion to land development.

For instance, I live in a medium size American city (actually, county), which is surrounded in all direction by rural (undeveloped) counties. On any given day throughout the year, our country is 2°F to 4°F warmer than the surrounding counties, in ANY direction (N,S,E, or W). My county is likely to have hundreds of times more temperature stations than the surrounding counties and therefore is more strongly biases the temperature data. This is generally the case all around the world.

